<h2 id="mocking-to-mock-dependencies">Mocking to mock dependencies</h2>
<ul>
<li>Mocking is one of the most crucial concepts in testing, especially
for Data Scientists and Data Engineers who deal with external resources
like databases, APIs, and cloud services.</li>
<li>Mocking is the act of replacing an actual object (like a database
connection, a web API call, or an external file read) with a stand-in
object (the "mock"). This stand-in object simulates the behavior of the
real object in a controlled way.</li>
<li>The core Python library for mocking is <code>unittest.mock</code>.
The most commonly used class is <code>Mock</code>.</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="the-core-concept-patching">The Core Concept: Patching</h3>
<p>To replace a real object with a mock, you use a technique called
<code>patching</code>. You tell Python's import system to swap out the
real object with your fake one for the duration of the test.</p>
<p><em>Example Scenario</em>: You have a function that loads user data
from an external REST API.</p>
