<span id="cb14-9"><a href="#cb14-9" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="cf">return</span> request.param</span>
<span id="cb14-10"><a href="#cb14-10" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb14-11"><a href="#cb14-11" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="kw">def</span> test_dtype_conversion(series_and_dtype):</span>
<span id="cb14-12"><a href="#cb14-12" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    series, expected_dtype <span class="op">=</span> series_and_dtype</span>
<span id="cb14-13"><a href="#cb14-13" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="co"># Imagine a function called convert_to_best_dtype(series)</span></span>
<span id="cb14-14"><a href="#cb14-14" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="co"># assert convert_to_best_dtype(series).dtype == expected_dtype</span></span>
<span id="cb14-15"><a href="#cb14-15" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    <span class="cf">pass</span></span></code></pre></div>
<h2 id="test-coverage">Test Coverage</h2>
<p>Code Coverage is a metric that describes the degree to which the
source code of a program is executed when a particular test suite is
run.</p>
<h3 id="how-to-use-pytest-cov">How to Use pytest-cov</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Step 1: Installation</strong></li>
</ul>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb15"><pre
class="sourceCode bash"><code class="sourceCode bash"><span id="cb15-1"><a href="#cb15-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ex">pip</span> install pytest pytest-cov</span></code></pre></div>
<ul>
<li><strong>Step 2: Running Coverage</strong></li>
</ul>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb16"><pre
class="sourceCode bash"><code class="sourceCode bash"><span id="cb16-1"><a href="#cb16-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># Measure coverage for the current directory/project</span></span>
<span id="cb16-2"><a href="#cb16-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ex">pytest</span> <span class="at">--cov</span><span class="op">=</span>. </span>
<span id="cb16-3"><a href="#cb16-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># OR, measure coverage for a specific package/module (e.g., &#39;my_package&#39;)</span></span>
<span id="cb16-4"><a href="#cb16-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># pytest --cov=my_package</span></span></code></pre></div>
<ul>
<li><strong>Step 3: Generating the HTML Report</strong></li>
</ul>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb17"><pre
class="sourceCode bash"><code class="sourceCode bash"><span id="cb17-1"><a href="#cb17-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ex">pytest</span> <span class="at">--cov</span><span class="op">=</span>. <span class="at">--cov-report</span> html</span></code></pre></div>
<p>You often want to prevent code with poor coverage from being merged.
pytest-cov allows you to enforce a minimum coverage threshold using the
--cov-fail-under flag</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb18"><pre
class="sourceCode bash"><code class="sourceCode bash"><span id="cb18-1"><a href="#cb18-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># This command will fail the test run if the total coverage is less than 90%</span></span>
<span id="cb18-2"><a href="#cb18-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="ex">pytest</span> <span class="at">--cov</span><span class="op">=</span>. <span class="at">--cov-fail-under</span><span class="op">=</span>90</span></code></pre></div>
<h2 id="integration-testing-example-etl-pipeline">Integration Testing
Example: ETL Pipeline</h2>
<p><strong>The Scenario: Data Ingestion and Transformation</strong> We
want to test a pipeline that combines three components:</p>
<ol type="1">
<li>Source: A file reader (e.g., reading a local CSV, or simulating a
database pull).</li>
<li>Transformation: A Python function that cleans and processes the
data.</li>
<li>Sink: A function that writes the processed data to its final
destination (e.g., a file, database, or API).</li>
</ol>
<p>The goal of the integration test is to confirm that if Component 1
produces data, Component 2 transforms it correctly, and Component 3
successfully saves the final result.</p>
<p>Assume we have</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb19"><pre
class="sourceCode python"><code class="sourceCode python"><span id="cb19-1"><a href="#cb19-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># data_cleaner.py - Component 2 (Transformation)</span></span>
<span id="cb19-2"><a href="#cb19-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb19-3"><a href="#cb19-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="im">import</span> pandas <span class="im">as</span> pd</span>
<span id="cb19-4"><a href="#cb19-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
